This would be a case where C99 style designated initializers would come in handy in C++.<p>For example if you have a struct like:<p><pre><code>  struct data {
      double w;
      double x;
      double y;
      double z;
  };
</code></pre>
You can then create a struct of that type using syntax like:<p><pre><code>  struct data d = {.w = 1.0, .x = 1.0, .y = 1.0, .z = 1.0};
</code></pre>
Then you could have your functions take a struct data as a parameter, and use designated initializers to have syntax for keyword parameters.<p>I&#x27;m not sure why this feature never made its way into a C++ standard over the years.
